**Summary:** The introduction (ch. 0, §5) explicitly defers the definition to chapter 1, which is titled "What the author means by the word liberty." There, Dunoyer defines *liberté* as **power** — specifically, "the power that man acquires to use his forces more easily as he frees himself from the obstacles that originally hindered their exercise." Liberty grows as a man removes the causes that prevent him from using his faculties, whether those causes are internal (ignorance, infirmity, vice) or external (injustice of others). Citations: `charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce`, ch. 1, paragraphs `p-fc8999` and `p-51f10e`.
